{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_halma_ver01/data/sn83016758/00280767748/1907110701/0368.xml":{"full_text":"v\nTHE PRINCETON UNION\n\\BY R. O. DUNN.\nTIRM8-S1.0 0 PER YEAR IN ADVANCE.\n1.25 I NOT PAID IN ADVANCE.\nOPPIOBI FIRST ST EAST OF COURTHOUSE.\nQ. I. STAPLES.\nBusiness Manager.\nis news.\nTHOS. H. PROWSB,\nEditor.\nThe reason why lumber is so high\nbut then there is really no reason why\nit should be.\nSince the financial disturbance has\nset in there has been a suspension of\ntrust-busting.\nThere is no doubt that those Wall\nstreet gamblers ought to be jailed, but\nhow are we going to accomplish it?\nIt doesn't necessarily follow that\nbecause Harry Thaw is studying law\nhe is crazy as declared by the alien\nists.\nIn flaming headlines the Minneapo-\nlis Tribune announces that Governor\nJohnson will seek a third term. That\nA daily advises us to hold our\ncopper stocks. Just about now we\nwould be mighty thankful could we\nhold our copper cents.\nOne great advantage in aerial teleg-\nraphy is that no possibiliby exists of\nbeing killed by coming into contact\nwith the system's live wires.\nNow is a splendid time for the Ameri-\ncan Society of Equity to practice what\nit preachesdo not dump farmers'\nproduce on a falling market.\nA New York paper says that a de-\ntermined effort will be made to clean\nout Tammany. A cleaning out of Wall\nstreet would prove of more general\nbenefit.\nThe action of the farmers' national\ncongress in passing a resolution rec\nommending a discontinuance of the\nfree seed farce should meet with gen\neral approbation.\nPeople are peculiar. They will\nstrain their necks to watch a gasbag\nfloating o'er their heads when they\ncan run across a dozen of them every\nday as they go to dinner.\nEven though John Rockefeller be\na thief and an unscrupulous person\ngenerally there are many who will\nmake no attempt to deny that he was\nof kin to them after he dies.\nJ. Adam Bede spoke last night at\nthe Minneapolis harvest dinner on\n\"How to Fa rm the Farmers.\"Aitkin\nRepublican.\nA subject upon which he is of course\nwell posted.\nThe army officers who were afraid\nto take the test horseback ride ordered\nby the president should be retired\nfrom the service. They have either\noutgrown their usefulness or mistaken\ntheir calling.\nA prominent St. Paul banker said\nto the writer last Saturday: \"Within\nten days or two weeks money will be\nforthcoming to handle the crops of the\nnorthwest, and it will be largely owing\nto the efforts of Hill.\"\nThe Duluth Herald hands out this\nlittle nosegay for Mr. Young to sniff\nat: \"There isn't quite enough hard\nship about Attorney General Young's\n'martyrdom' to make it realistic\nenough for campaign purposes.\"\nA general circulation and diligent\nreading of Thackeray's \"Book of\nSnobs\" wouldn't hurt some sections\nof Duluth.Mary McFadden.\nAnglophobiacs from Noo Yawk with\nmonocles and turned up trousers must\nhave invaded Duluth.\nAs the selling of postage stamps on\nSunday in Canadian hotels is prohib\nited by law the postoffice authorities\nhave decided to install slot machines\nfor public accommodation. The laws\nof Canada are altogether too puritan\nical.\nMany of the national banks holding\ngovernment deposits have decided to\ntake advantage of the comptroller of\nthe currency's proposition and substi-\ntute other bonds for those of the Unit-\ned States deposited in the treasury.\nThey will thus be enabled to use the\nbonds so released as a basis for\nnew circulation, and this increased\ncirculation will have the effect of re-\nlieving the money situation.\nNews from New Yo rk says that\nStuyvesant Chanler has been chosen\nby Tammany for the head of the dem-\nocratic presidential ticket and John-\nson for the tail. Mr. Bryan should\nnot, however, feel cast down. Tam\nmanyjs a long ways from being the\ndemocratic party.\nOnly a few months ago there was a\nterrible rumpus kicked up in several\nsouthern states because of injunctions\nissued by federal courts to enjoin the\nenforcement of the two cent passenger\nrate laws, now the governors of these\nsame states are balking of calling ex-\ntra sessions of the legislature to\nrepeal the law.\nIt may be only a stock-jobbers'\npanic but it is affecting the entire\nbusiness of the country just the same,\nand notwithstanding the optimistic\nbone of the press and eminent finan-\nciers the end is not yet in sight.\nFrenzied finance and pestiferous polit-\nical demagogues are responsible for\nthe present deplorable condition of\nbusiness affairs.\nIn view of the fact that numerous\npeople have been inclined bo hold him\nresponsible for the recent financial\ndifficulties President Roosevelt has\ndecided to revise his annual message\nin order that he may treat more fully\nthe question of high finance. It\nwould be just as reasonable to accuse\nMr. Bryan of bringing about the\nmoney disturbance as it is Mr. Roose-\nvelt.\nWe do not for a moment believe\nthat Hon. S. A Langum, secretary of\nthe Minnesota state senate, is in the\nslightest degree responsible for the\nchange made in senate file No 509\nwhereby the salary of the public ex-\naminer was fixed at $4,500 instead of\n$4,100 as the legislature intended.\nNevertheless we are convinced from\ninformation imparted at the state cap-\nitol that the \"change\" was not the re-\nsult of a mere \"clerical error.\"\nConde Hamlin, for many years the\nefficient business manager of the St.\nPaul Pioneer Press, is now business\nmanager of one of the great dailies of\nNew Yorkthe Tribune. Mr. Hamlin\nhas a national reputation as a suc-\ncessful newspaper^ man. is not\nonly a gentleman of splendid business\nabilities but he is also a gifted writer.\nHis many friends in Minnesota will\nrejoice to learn of his good fortune\nin being given the management of one\nof the greatest newspapers of the\ncountry.\nStreet car and other public service\ncorporations should be taxed on their\ngross earnings and the state should\nreceive its pro ra ta share. The rate\nshould be such as would oblige the\ncorporations to bear their just pro-\nportion of the burdens of taxation.\nAs long as public service corpora-\ntions are assessed on a direct valu-\nation basis just so long will the incen-\ntive remain for officers of those cor-\nporations to attempt to unduly influ-\nence assessors, boards of equalization\nand executive officers.\nEven the Twin City newspapers are\nbeginning to admit that probably the\nwide open tax amendment to the con\nstitution was defeated at the last elec\ntion. The recount of 136,196 votes in\n611 precincts shows that the tax\namendment lacked 1,525 votes neces\nsary for its adoption. Good lawyers\nsay that the courts will assume that\nthe election officers and canvassing\nboards did their duty and that the re\nturns from the precincts that have not\nbeen recounted are correct. The case\nis being heard in the St. Louis\ncounty district court today.\nIf the state board of control is to be\nconverted into a gigantic political\nmachine the next legislature should\nwipe it out of existence. Th main\nreason for the creation of the board\nof control and the abolishment of the\nhydra-headed local board system was\na more economical administration of\nthe affairs of the charitable, correc\ntional and penal institutions of the\nstate and the divorcement of the state\ninstitutions from politics. Th chief\nduties of the members of the present\nboard of control seem to consist of\ndrawing their salaries and creating\nsinecures for Governor Johnson's\nhenchmen. I it any wonder that the\ntax levy for state purposes is soaring\nskyward?\n^THB PKrKCBTO^ TJN\nSENSIBLE SENATOR HANSSBOVGH.\nSenator Hansbrough of Nortfa\nDakota is alive to the intersts of that\nstate, and the business men and farm-\ners of Minnesota will also have reason\nto feel grateful to him if the sugges-\ntions contained in the following tele-\ngram sent to the president from Grand\nForks on Monday are favorably acted\nupon:\n\"Fully 150,000,000 bushels of grain\nare now ready to be marketed in the\ntwo Dakotas and Minnesota, and\nthere is no money with which to do it.\nThe necessities of the northwest are,\ntherefore, much greater than in any\nother section of the country, demand\ning the fullest consideration at the\nhands of the treasury department.\n\"Ten million dollars placed in twin\ncity banks would raise the embargo\nand start grain shipments to Europe.\nThis would relieve the financial stress\nin the east much quicker than a depos\nit of treasury funds in New York.\n\"Treasury relief operations should\nhave been begun here, where the con\ngestion is greatest. Our people are\nnot losing their heads. They have no\nfear of a panic, but in this crop-mov\ning season our business men should\nhave special consideration.\"\nColonel Alvaren Allen, one of the\nsturdy pioneers of the state, died at\nthe Merchants hotel in St. Paul last\nFriday afternoon. Colonel Allen was\nborn in New York state in 1822, came\nto the territory of Minnesota in 1851\nand settled in St. Anthony Falls,\nwhere he engaged in the livery busi-\nness and was connected with several\nstage lines later he moved to St. Paul,\nwhere he followed the same line of\nbusiness and also figured as a rail-\nroad contractor in 1873 he purchased\nan interest in the Merchants hotel and\nlater became the sole owner. He built\nup the Merchants and made it the fa-\nvorite hotel of the twin cities. He\nretired from the active management of\nthe hotel in 1887, but was more or less\nidentified with it until 1899. The col-\nonel was a genial, whole-souled man,\nand although he lived to a ripe old\nage his death will be regretted \"by\nthousands of personal friends and ac-\nquaintances in Minnesota and\nthroughout the northwest generally.\nJournal.\nwmmsmm\nI\nWe could never understand why\nevery member of the American Society\nof Equity was required to subscribe\nfor Up-to-Date Farming, owned aj)d\nedited by A Everitt, national pres-\nident of the society. A weekly news-\npaper with a circulation of over 100,-\n000 must have been a gold mine to its\npublisher. The principles enunciated\nby Up-to-Date Farming were in the\nmain correct, but on the whole it was\npoorly edited. A the recent annual\nnational convention of the society in\nIndianapolis C. M. Barnett of Ken-\ntucky was elected to succeed Mr.\nEveritt as president, and it was also\nvoted that Up-to-Date Farming would\nno longer be the official organ of the\nsociety, but that the society would\nown and control its own organ which\nwould soon be established and would\nbe known as Th Equity Farm\nNowhere in the United States is\nthere any financial panic, crisis or\neven serious embarrassment except in\nNew Yo rk city and Pittsburg. Even\nin New Yo rk the only financial insti\ntutions affected are those whose offi\ncers went into oubside speculation\nwith other people's money.New York\nWorld.\nThat's it exactlyspeculating with\nother people's money, gambling in\nstocks without caring a rap whether\nthose who intrusted them with their\nmoney ever receive a cent of it back.\nRunning no risk of personal loss\nthese unscrupulous gamblers plunge\nand plunge until they bring about a\ncondition of financial panic.\nCharlemagne Tower has tired of his\njob as ambassador to Berlin with its\npaltry $17,500 a year and will quit im\nmediately a successor is found. But\nit takes a rich man to hold down that\nambassadorship and a man who is\nwilling to put his hand in his pocket\nfor something like $100,000 annually.\nMr. Tower's house rent alone exceeds\nthe amount of his salary, and to live\nin a less pretentious residence would\ndisgrace our nation in the eyes of\nGermany. The United States govern\nment is altogether too stingy. It\nshould pay an ambassador at least\n$25,000 a year and all expenses.\nPaying out a man's private fortune\nfor the sake of honor will tire even\na multimilionaire in the course of\ntime.\n^ii^tWsA)BL^^-!at &r I^^^^JA^^^^\nMartin Brands and His Umbrella.\nMartin Brands' trip to Minneapolis\nlast week cost him a fine silk umbrella\nthat is the umbrella was spirited\naway. was strolling down Wash\nington avenue when he stopped to\npurchase a paper from a newsboy.\nHaving a package in his left hand\nand an umbrella in the right, he was\ncompelled to relinquish one or the\nother in order to draw forth his\npocketbook. S he placed the um\nbrella at the entrance of a stairway\nwhile he paid for the paper. Upon\nreaching for the umbrella a minute\nlater he found that it had disappeared\nsomeone had supposedly gumshoed\ndown the stairway and appropriated\nthe article. Martin has decided that\nupon every occasion hereafter when\nhe visits Minneapolis he will attach\nhis umbrella to his wrist by means of\na chain. I believe.\" he says, \"that\nthe crooks of Washington avenue\ncould remove a man's false teeth with\nout his knowledge.\"\nJ. H. Arnnold Encounters a Snag.\nPractically no damage to property\nwas sustained on Hallowe'en. A\nnumber of gates, signs, etc., were car\nried away but they were recovered\nagain, and an effigy was hung to a\ntelephone post on the school house\ngrounds which the janitor had diffi\nculty in getbing down. He succeeded\nin climbing half way to the dummy\nand then slid down again, leaving\nabout a square foot of his trousers\nattached to the pole. This made him\na trifle angry and he would probably\nhave used language unbecoming a\ngentleman had not a bevy of school\nma'ams been 'passing at the time.\nThey laughed, of course, and he\nlaughed with them. Donning a pair\nof overalls the janitor then hied to the\ntelephone office, where he borrowed a\npair of climbers and eventually suc\nceeded in reaching the effigy and\nyanking it down.\nOld Soldier Conveyed to State Home.'\nK. Archer, a veteran of the civil\nwar, who for five weeks had been under\ntreatment at the Northwestern hospital,\nwas on Tuesday conveyed to the state\nsoldiers' home. David Whitcomb ac\ncompanied Mr. Archer to that institu\ntion. About six weeks ago Mr. Arch\ner became paralyzed on the right side\nand was also rendered speechless by\nthe stroke. A week later he was re\nmoved to the Northwestern hospital at\nthis place and remained until he had\nsufficiently recovered to be taken to\nthe soldiers' home. When he left here\nhe could talk as well as ever and was\nin a jovial frame of mind.\nFritz Kunkel In Poor Circumstances.\nFritz Kunkel, who resides in the\neastern end of Princeton township, is\nerecting a new residence on the site of\nthe old one that was destroyed by fire\nseveral weeks ago. Fritz had only a\nsmall insurance and while he is not\nbegging for assistance he is a poor\nman with a large family to care for.\nVery little clothing or furniture was\nsaved from the fire. An charitably\ndisposed individual who wishes to as\nsist Mr. Kunkel can reach him\nthrough the Union office.\nA Prosperous Creamery.\nWhile in conversation with Supt.\nFox of the West Branch creamery on\nTuesday that gentleman said that\nbusiness was highly gratifying to the\nassociationthat more cream is being\nreceived than ever before at this sea\nson of the year. The price paid by\nthe West Branch creamery on Tues\nday for butterfat was 27 cents. This\nis three or four cents more than has\nbeen paid by the agents of centraliz\ning concerns, says Mr. Fox\nFirst White Children Born Here\nFifty years ago last Saturday the\nfirst white girls twins born in\nPrincton, arrived at the home of\nMr. and Mrs. C. H. Chadbourne, who\nat that time lived on the north side.\nMr. Chadbourne says that upon that\ndate, November 2, 1857, there was ice\non the Rum river of sufficient thick\nness to permit of teams crossing over\nit. The first white male child born in\nPrinceton was C. Cater, who ar\nrived in February, 1858.\nC. X. Robinson Visits His Kancli.\nMrs. C. N Robinson of Minneapo\nlis arrived here on Thursday to visit\nMr. and Mrs. C. Borden. The fol\nlowing day Mr. Robinson came up\nand on Sunday he and Mr. Borden\ndrove to Onamia to look over a tract\nof land near there owned by Mr. Rob\ninson which is being prepared for a\nsheep ranch. In the spring the ranch\nwill be stocked. Mr. and Mrs Rob\ninson returned to Minneapolis on\nMonday morning.\nDow Wrestles With Slush.\nOn Friday the village water tank\nwas cleaned out and a new cement\nbottom placed in the same. Electri\ncian Dow and a couple of assistants\nperformed the cleaning operation and\nMr. Dow remained in the slush at the\nbottom of the tank until the last buck\netfull had been removed. When he\ncame forth he was a sight to behold.\nHunters Start for Deer Country.\nMagnus Sjoblom, Andrew Bullis\nand Adel Holm left on Monday night's\ntrain for the deer hunting grounds\nnorth of Duluth. They were the ad\nvance guard of a larger party which\nwill follow today, and went forth to\nprepare the camp and spot the game.\nWe expect a wireless message from\nthem within a few days.\n1\\\n(tggmil\nMfc\nFall Is the\n11T1G\n**ugs Bu\nMakes the home warmer and more pleasant for the long\nwinter. We have just received a large assortment of\nVELVET AND BRUSSELS RUGS\nin carefully selected patterns and warm colorings for\nthe fall trade. We are cleaning up our stock of\nROLL CARPETING AND HATTING\nby selling at prices that will make it an object for you\nto buy now. We have bought our stock for next spring\nand the roll carpeting and matting now on hand must\nbe sold this fall, hence we have cut off our profit and\nquote prices that will make you buy. We also call your\nattention to our line of\nTRUNKS AND SUIT CASES\nBought at aright price and with a view of your needs.\nCome in and see for yourself we may have just what\nyou want.\nCaley Hardware Co\nST. PAUL j&\nBUSINESS\nJ& J&\nCor. 7t hand Wabasha, St Paul, ilinn.\nW give our students a thorough Business Education.\nW place them in good positions FREE.\nW furnish books FREE.\nOur graduates receive from $50 to $150 per month salary.\nIf you wish to be in line for a similar salary, take advantage of\nthis offer and enroll with S for a COMBINED COURSE\nin either Day or Night School.\nSpecial $5.00 Free Offer\nCut this COUPON out and mail it or present it at the St. Paul\nBusiness College, corner 7th and Wabasha, before December 1, 1907,\nand W E will give you a RECEIPT for $5.00 on your tuition.\n*^I4P^^^^^V^* ll I ^M^^^M^P^M^^Si^^^l\nAre You \"Long\"\non Underwear?\nIf \"short\" you better cover immediately by buying\na suit of our natural wool or camel's\nhair under garments\n$2.00 and $3.00 per Suit.\nMen's Union Suits $1.00, $1.50, $2.00, $3.00\nThe celebrated \"Munsing\"unexcelled for wear and\ncomfort, per garment\n$1.50, $2.50 and $3.50.\nFleeced garments for men and boys 25c and 50c\nBoys' Suits and Overcoats\nCheviots, Scotches and Meltons, two and three pieced'\nknee pants suits for\n$1.50, 2.00, 2.50 and 3.00.\nThree pieced long pants suits $3.50 and $5.00\nDress Shirts\nWhite muslin pleated Madras, percale and dainty 71\ncords, coat and regular styles, all sizes $l.OO,\nMercerized and embroidered bosom shirts, in\nneat shades of tan and grey 50c\\\nZ5fe\nAvery Clothing House\ntjAji\n1\ni. wi wiwwm i 'M^^^\nand Carpeting\nJ&\nCOLLEGE","height":"26202","width":"18363"}}
